[2] Taiwan ex Tonga
Date: Thu 10 Apr 2008
Source: The China Post, Central News Agency (CNA) report [edited]
<http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/local/taipei/2008/04/10/151194/Imported-dengue.htm>


The Department of Health (DOH) confirmed the 1st imported cluster
cases of dengue fever discovered in a family yesterday [9 Apr 2008].

Chou Chih-hao, deputy director of the DOH's Centers for Disease
Control, said the patients were 4 children born to a Tongese mother
who was married to a Taiwanese man living in Taipei County.

Chou said the mother took her 4 children to visit Tonga, a South
Pacific island nation near New Zealand, and brought the children back
to Taiwan on 24 Mar [2008]. Her 4-year-old son was detected to have a
fever at the airport and was confirmed to have been infected with the
mosquito-borne disease.

Taipei County health authorities then took specimens from the mother
and her 3 daughters aged 8, 10, and 13. Tests confirmed that the 3
sisters were also infected, although the mother was not. But "only
one sister showed symptoms of fever on 28 Mar [2008], and the 2
others had no symptoms," Chou said, adding that all 4 children
recovered after taking medicine.

The centers estimated that there have been 24 imported dengue fever
cases so far this year [2008], compared with only 15 imported cases
during the same period last year [2007].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[ProMED-mail reported over 200 dengue cases in Tonga as of 2 Mar 2008
(see archive no. 20080309.0962). One would infer from the report
above of dengue cases showing up in Taiwan that the epidemic in Tonga
continues. ProMED would appreciate further information from Tonga
concerning the dengue outbreak there.

A map of the Tonga islands and their location in the South Pacific
can be accessed at
<http://www.infoplease.com/atlas/country/tonga.html>. - Mod.TY]

