[3] Cambodia
Date: Thu 10 Apr 2008
Source: China View, Xinhua News Agency report [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-04/10/content_7951864.htm>


[An] expert has warned that a dengue fever epidemic would soon sweep
through Cambodia at a time when infections of the disease are usually
at their lowest, the Mekong Times newspaper said Thursday [10 Apr
2008].

Generally, dengue fever is most prevalent from early January till May
in Cambodia, but this year [2008] the worst period will be from the
end of April till July, claimed Ngan Chantha, vice director of
National Center For Dengue and Malaria Control.

Ngan Chantha said the change has resulted from many factors such as
the impact of the dengue epidemic in late 2007 and environmental
changes that have altered the existing virus and irregular rainfall.

Other subordinate factors such as unsanitary conditions and migration
exacerbate the problem, he said.

However, a combined Health Ministry and National Center Against
Dengue Fever campaign dubbed "Abate", an insecticide used to kill
mosquito larvae, should go some way towards reducing the risk, Ngan
Chantha said.

Officials are distributing Abate to people in high-risk areas for
them to add to their water storage to kill the _Anopheles_ mosquito
larvae that spread dengue fever when they reach adulthood. [This
statement is incorrect. _Aedes aegypti_ and possibly _Ae. albopictus_
are dengue virus vectors, not _Anopheles_ spp. mosquitoes. - Mod.TY]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[There is no information provided that supports the statement that
changing environmental conditions have altered the virus. The
epidemiology (that is, patterns of transmission) may have been
altered by environmental changes, but not the virus per se.

A map of Cambodia can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/cambodia_pol_97.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[4] Thailand
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2008
Source: China View, Xinhua News Agency report [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-04/08/content_7939130.htm>


Thailand's Public Health Minister Chaiya Sasomsub on Tuesday [8 Apr
2008] warned the public to keep alert to the dengue fever, as 9
people have died and over 7000 suffered from the disease during the
1st quarter of 2008.

During the 1st 3 months of this year [2008], the cumulative number of
patients soared to 7413, with 99 percent of them completely
recovered, Chaiya was quoted by the Thai News Agency as saying.
However, there were 9 fatalities in 8 provinces, he said.

The number of victims increased from the same period of last year
[2007], when there were 4209 patients and 4 dengue fatalities, the
minister said.

Chaiya said he had instructed local health officials nationwide to
maintain the campaign to eradicate the mosquito breeding habitats.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[A map of Thailand can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/thailand_admin_2005.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

