[5] Malaysia
Date: Sat 5 Apr 2008
Source: The Earth Times [edited]
<http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/196892,dengue-cases-on-the-rise-in-malaysia-death-toll-reaches.html>


Malaysia continues to battle a steady rise in the number of dengue
cases for the 1st 3 months of the year [2008] as the death toll from
the mosquito-borne disease reached 26, a news report said Saturday [5
Apr 2008]. From January-March [2008], a total of 9889 people were
diagnosed with dengue and 26 of them died, the ministry's director of
disease control Hasan Abdul Rahman was quoted as saying by the New
Straits Times daily.

Last year [2007], there were a total 13 949 cases with 34 deaths from
January to March [2007].

Hasan said although the number of cases this year [2008] was lower
than last year [2007], the number of dengue victims increased from
month-to-month. He blamed the rise on weather conditions, which made
it conducive for the virus-carrying _Aedes_ mosquito to breed.

The central Selangor state recorded the most cases at 262, followed
by the capital Kuala Lumpur and the southern state of Johor, he said.

Last week, health ministry officials issued 144 compound notices on
houses and shops where the _Aedes_ mosquitoes were found breeding.
The _Aedes_ mosquito breeds in clear and stagnant water, such as
flower vases, uncovered barrels, buckets, and discarded tires.

The government has been holding campaigns to educate the public as
well as conduct checks on residential and construction sites in
efforts to stem the steady rise in dengue cases.

However, despite the efforts, the number of cases and deaths continue
to rise each year.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[A map of Malaysia showing its administrative divisions can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/malaysia_adm98.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

