[6] Singapore
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2008
Source: M&C [edited]
<http://news.monstersandcritics.

com/health/news/article_1398820.php/Singapore_fears_its_worst-ever_dengue_fever_epidemic>


Dengue fever infections are mounting alarmingly in Singapore due to a
change to a more deadly strain of the disease, sparking fears of the
city-state's potentially worst epidemic yet news reports said Tuesday
[8 Apr 2008].

Unless the trend of infections is halted, health officials warn that
the number of sick people could hit record levels within 3 years.

The number of infections from January through March [2008] is already
60 percent higher than during the 1st quarter of 2007, said figures
published in The Straits Times. "If nothing is done to stop the
spread, the number of cases will increase very significantly," Dr Ng
Lee Ching, head of the Environmental Health Institute, was quoted as
saying.

The severe, flu-like illness is showing up in a more deadly form,
called dengue haemorrhagic fever, for which there is no vaccine or
cure, Ng said. Victims can only be treated for the symptoms, which
include high fever, body aches and nausea; 20 people died from it
last year [2007].

Experts are further concerned because the _Aedes_ mosquito, which
spreads the disease [virus], appears to be moving into areas where it
previously was not found.

The city-state is spending 200 000 Singapore dollars (USD 145 000) a
day in a massive effort to destroy breeding sites and a targeted war
against mosquitoes in areas where 2 or more people fall ill.

Last year [2007], more than 5000 homeowners were fined 200 Singapore
dollars (USD 145) for allowing mosquitoes to breed. Construction
sites found with the insect pests breeding are fined 2000 Singapore
dollars (USD 1459).

'We cannot understand why the numbers are climbing,' Ng said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[The observation that the _Aedes_ dengue virus vector is showing up
in new areas may account for increasing numbers of dengue cases.
Previously, Singapore had been successful in controlling _Aedes_
populations through elimination of its breeding sites. One hopes that
the current campaign will achieve the same degree of success, and
serve as a model for other countries, especially in Southeast Asia
where 2008 is becoming a severe dengue outbreak year.

A map of Singapore can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/singapore_pol_05.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

