[11] Saint Martin
Date: Thu 10 Apr 2008
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point Epidemiologique no. 13
[in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_st_barth_100408/PEP_SBSM_2008_13_dengue.pdf>



Since the beginning of March [2008], over the last 6 weeks, the
number of clinically suspected dengue cases remains stable around the
epidemic threshold (33 cases estimated last week [week of 31 Mar
2008]). The dynamics of laboratory confirmed cases is similar.

Since the beginning of the epidemic (2nd week of November), it is
estimated that there has been a total of about 2010 cases clinically
compatible with dengue. Over the same period, the number of
hospitalized laboratory confirmed dengue cases was 21 including 13
adults (including 9 serious forms [of the disease]) and 8 children
(presenting only common [classical dengue] forms).

Since mid-November [2007], the surveillance of [dengue virus]
serotypes has detected DEN-1.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The accuracy of the dengue diagnosis has now been laboratory
confirmed and the dengue virus circulating there has been identified
as DEN-1.

A map showing the location of the French overseas collectivity of
Saint Martin in the Caribbean can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/stmartin.htm>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[12] Saint Barthelemy
Date: Thu 10 Apr 2008
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point Epidemiologique no. 13
[in French, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_st_barth_100408/PEP_SBSM_2008_13_dengue.pdf>


For nearly 4 months, the number of clinically suspected dengue cases
stabilized at around 10-30 cases weekly, remaining at a level close
to the epidemic threshold. The same dynamic is observed in laboratory
confirmed cases.

Since the beginning of the pre-alert in mid-November [2007], it is
estimated that 460 people went to a general practice physician for a
syndrome compatible with dengue. During this same period, 6 adults
with severe forms [of dengue infection] were hospitalised.

Since December 2007, DEN [virus] serotype 1, has been most often
identified; serotype [dengue virus] DEN 2 has also been circulating.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map showing the location of the French overseas collectivity of
Saint Barthelemy in the Caribbean can be accessed at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/stbarts.htm>.

